In [31]:
nltk.download('words')

Review = food.loc[:, ['Score', 'Text']].copy()
y
stop_words = set(ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS)
english_vocab = set(w.lower() for w in words.words())


def preprocess_text(sentence: str) -> str:

    sentence = str(sentence).lower()
    sentence = re.sub(r'[^a-z\s]', ' ', sentence)
    tokens = [
        word
        for word in sentence.split()
        if (
            word not in stop_words
            and len(word) > 2
            and word in english_vocab
        )
    ]

    return " ".join(tokens).strip()

Review['cleaned_review'] = Review['Text'].apply(preprocess_text)
print("Review dataframe after preprocessing")
print(Review.head())

In [34]:
bigram_vectorizer = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=(2, 2), stop_words="english")
bigram_matrix = bigram_vectorizer.fit_transform(Review["cleaned_review"])

bigram_freq = bigram_matrix.sum(axis=0).A1
bigram_terms = bigram_vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()

bigram_data = (
    pd.DataFrame({"Bigram": bigram_terms, "Count": bigram_freq})
    .sort_values("Count", ascending=False)
    .head(20)
)


trigram_vectorizer = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=(3, 3), stop_words="english")
trigram_matrix = trigram_vectorizer.fit_transform(Review["cleaned_review"])

trigram_freq = trigram_matrix.sum(axis=0).A1
trigram_terms = trigram_vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()

trigram_data = (
    pd.DataFrame({"Trigram": trigram_terms, "Count": trigram_freq})
    .sort_values("Count", ascending=False)
    .head(20)
)


fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6))


axes[0].barh(bigram_data["Bigram"], bigram_data["Count"], color="skyblue")
axes[0].set_title("Top 20 Bigrams", fontsize=14)
axes[0].invert_yaxis()

# Plot trigrams
axes[1].barh(trigram_data["Trigram"], trigram_data["Count"], color="salmon")
axes[1].set_title("Top 20 Trigrams", fontsize=14)
axes[1].invert_yaxis()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In [36]:
tfidf = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=5000)
X_tfidf = tfidf.fit_transform(X)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_tfidf, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42
)

model_tfidf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42).fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred_tfidf = model_tfidf.predict(X_test)

print("TF-IDF Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_tfidf))


print("\nClassification Report (TF-IDF):\n")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_tfidf))

ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_tfidf)).plot(cmap="Blues")
plt.title("TF-IDF Confusion Matrix")
plt.show()

c) Comparison TFIDF and BoW

Results Comparison:

Comparator TF-IDF BoW Better
Accuracy 0.7046 0.7086 BoW
Class 1 (Very Negative) F1 0.56 0.57 BoW
Class 2 (Negative) F1 0.41 0.42 BoW
Class 3 (Neutral) F1 0.42 0.42 Tie
Class 4 (Positive) F1 0.47 0.47 Tie
Class 5 (Very Positive) F1 0.83 0.83 Tie
Macro Avg F1 0.54 0.54 Tie
Weighted Avg F1 0.70 0.70 Tie (BoW recall slightly higher)
Feature TF-IDF (Term Frequency–Inverse Document Frequency) BoW (Bag of Words)
Weighting Assigns higher weight to rare but important words, lower weight to common words. Treats all words equally, only counts frequency.
Captures Importance Yes (considers global importance of words). No (only considers local frequency in a document).
Dimensionality Similar to BoW, but with weighted values. High dimensional (sparse vectors).
Handling Stopwords Naturally reduces influence of common words like “the”, “is”, etc. Stopwords may dominate without manual removal.
Interpretability Scores represent relevance of words in documents. Easy to understand (just word counts).
Model Performance Usually better for text classification tasks (less noise, more informative features). May work well for simple tasks but less effective with large vocabularies.
Computational Cost Slightly higher (needs IDF calculation). Lower (just counts word frequencies).
Use Case Best when importance of words matters (sentiment analysis, classification). Best for simple frequency-based tasks (text clustering, keyword extraction).

nlp = spacy.load("en_core_web_sm")


long_reviews = Review[Review['cleaned_review'].str.split().str.len() >= 10]['cleaned_review']
samples = random.sample(list(long_reviews), 2)

for idx, sent in enumerate(samples, 1):
    doc = nlp(sent)
    print(f"\nSentence {idx}: {sent}\n")

    displacy.render(
        doc,
        style="dep",
        jupyter=True,
        options={"distance": 120, "compact": True, "color": "blue", "bg": "white"}
    )


    dep_data = []
    for token in doc:
        dep_data.append({
            "Token": token.text,
            "POS": token.pos_,
            "Dependency": token.dep_,
            "Head": token.head.text
        })

    df = pd.DataFrame(dep_data)
    print(f"\nDependency Table for Sentence {idx}:\n")
    display(df)

    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.sanitize_html]
--writer=<DottedObjectName>
    Writer class used to write the
                                        results of the conversion
    Default: 'FilesWriter'
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.writer_class]
--post=<DottedOrNone>
    PostProcessor class used to write the
                                        results of the conversion
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.postprocessor_class]
--output=<Unicode>
    Overwrite base name use for output files.
                Supports pattern replacements '{notebook_name}'.
    Default: '{notebook_name}'
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.output_base]
--output-dir=<Unicode>
    Directory to write output(s) to. Defaults
                                  to output to the directory of each notebook. To recover
                                  previous default behaviour (outputting to the current
                                  working directory) use . as the flag value.
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--FilesWriter.build_directory]
--reveal-prefix=<Unicode>
    The URL prefix for reveal.js (version 3.x).
            This defaults to the reveal CDN, but can be any url pointing to a copy
            of reveal.js.
            For speaker notes to work, this must be a relative path to a local
            copy of reveal.js: e.g., "reveal.js".
            If a relative path is given, it must be a subdirectory of the
            current directory (from which the server is run).
            See the usage documentation
            (https://nbconvert.readthedocs.io/en/latest/usage.html#reveal-js-html-slideshow)
            for more details.
    Default: ''
    Equivalent to: [--SlidesExporter.reveal_url_prefix]
--nbformat=<Enum>
    The nbformat version to write.
            Use this to downgrade notebooks.
    Choices: any of [1, 2, 3, 4]
    Default: 4
    Equivalent to: [--NotebookExporter.nbformat_version]

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
